The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Rs 2cr bribe babu
                                                                                                                                 2                                                                                      Rs 2cr bribe babu
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                      Manjit Singh Bali                          
	Mumbai, Feb. 25: One of the highest ranking postal officials has been arrested by the CBI on the charge of accepting a bribe of Rs 2 crore he allegedly demanded for issuing a no-objection certificate for development of a plot reserved for a post office in Thane district.        
	Manjit Singh Bali, the chief postmaster-general of Maharashtra and Goa, was allegedly caught red-handed by the bureaus anti-corruption branch while he was accepting cash at the popular Moshes restaurant at Badhwar Park in upscale Cuffe Parade.         
	Bali, a 1978-batch Indian Postal Service officer, was accepting a bribe of Rs 1.25 crore, which was part of the total amount of Rs 2 crore allegedly demanded on his behalf by two middlemen from a former Congress councillor of Mira-Bhayander in Thane.         
	The postal big boss was arrested with middleman Harsh Dalmiya and his father Arun Dalmiya at the restaurant.         
	The CBI then raided Balis office as well as residence on the 11th floor of Belvedere highrise at Cumbala Hill in south Mumbai. The bureau said its teams seized cash of Rs 34 lakh during the searches along with foreign currencies  $10,722, 3050 and Euro 3,470. The money was packed neatly in four briefcases, a CBI officer said.        
	The agency also traced immovable assets at Faridabad, Panchkula and Dwarka in New Delhi, Bhopal and Gurgaon, valued at more than Rs 1 crore.         
	Rishi Raj Singh, the CBIs joint director (western zone), said Bali had demanded the bribe for issuing a no-objection certificate (NOC) for developing a plot of approximately 2,000 square metre at Naya Nagar under the Mira-Bhayander Municipal Corporation in Thane district.         
	The plot was reserved for a post office.                                                                                                                                                          
